A '''village idiot''' is a person well known in their community for their [[stupidity]] or ignorant behavior. The term first appears in the preface to [[George Bernard Shaw]]'s play ''[[Major Barbara]]'', which opened in [[1907]]. Shaw discusses how some people have treated [[madness]] or [[idiocy]] as a source of humor, remarking that "I myself have had a village idiot exhibited to me as something irresistibly funny." The underlying supposition is that in every small rustic town there resides a dimwitted individual whose fellow denizens regard him as very amusing.

[[Monty Python]] did a famous sketch about the idiot's role in society, where the idiot in question spoke about his role in an educated manner. Only as someone local went by, he reverted back to idiotic behaviour. He even lectured at a university on "idiot studies". It even portrayed the urban idiot as an upper class city gent.

